{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "f3460dbe-75ba-4b63-a621-6e693aa21c9b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Slicing - Lecture"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "69f3ffbd-3816-43f7-ada0-eceea9b2aa89",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We have used slicing before, now a deep dive\n",
    "\n",
    "Slicing reliex on indexing -> ony works with sequence types\n",
    "Mutable Sequence Types: Extract Data, Assign Data\n",
    "Immutable Sequence Types: Extract Data\n",
    "\n",
    "Ex/\n",
    "l = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\n",
    "l[0:2] -> [1, 2]\n",
    "l[0:2] = ('a', 'b', 'c')\n",
    "l -> ['a', 'b', 'b', 3, 4, 5]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "eb842c43-78d8-4b94-8fa5-a5eed2d08301",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The Slice Type\n",
    "\n",
    "We usually slice sequences in conventional notation\n",
    "\n",
    "my_list[i:j]\n",
    "\n",
    "Slice definitions are objects -> of type slice\n",
    "\n",
    "s = slice(0, 2)\n",
    "type(s) -> slice\n",
    "s.start -> 0\n",
    "s.end -> 2\n",
    "l = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\n",
    "l[s] -> [1, 2]\n",
    "\n",
    "Useful because we can name slices and use symbols instead of literal subsequently, similar to Excel."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "d38fff8f-0dd6-4cbb-ad7f-e2d8fe5afffb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Slice Start and Stop Bounds\n",
    "\n",
    "[i:j] start at i (including) stop at j (excluding); integers k where i <= k < j; zero-based\n",
    "\n",
    "Convenient to think of slices as\n",
    "\n",
    " a b c d e f\n",
    "0 1 2 3 4 5 6\n",
    "   -----  \n",
    "\n",
    "[1:4]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "37e57d94-942c-410b-963b-1a12be8b14d4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Effective Start and Stop Bounds\n",
    "\n",
    "The following works:\n",
    "l = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e', 'f']\n",
    "l[3:100] -> ['d', 'e', 'f']\n",
    "We can specificy slices that are out of bounds\n",
    "\n",
    "Negative indices work too:\n",
    "l[-1] -> 'f'\n",
    "l[-3:-1] -> ['d', 'e']\n",
    "\n",
    "  a b c d e f\n",
    " 0 1 2 3 4 5 6\n",
    "-6-5-4-3-2-1"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "51de9c6c-1dd4-47ff-99cc-0521fedea36f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Step Value\n",
    "\n",
    "Slices also support a third argument - the step value\n",
    "[i:j:k] (aka stride)\n",
    "slice(i, j, k)\n",
    "\n",
    "When not specified the step value defaults to 1\n",
    "\n",
    "    0    1    2    3    4    5\n",
    "l = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e', 'f']\n",
    "   -6   -5   -4   -3   -2   -1\n",
    "\n",
    "l[0:6:2] 0, 2, 4 -> ['a', 'c', 'e']\n",
    "l[1:6:3] 1, 4 -> ['b', 'e']\n",
    "l[1:15:3] 1, 4 -> ['b', 'e']\n",
    "l[-1:-4:-1] -1, -2, -3 -> ['f', 'e', 'd']"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "bcfbc289-01f5-43cd-ba61-c6a0a62275b9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Range Equivalence\n",
    "\n",
    "Slice defines sequence of indices that is used to select elements for another sequence\n",
    "Indices defined by a slice can be defined using a range\n",
    "The difference is that slices are defined independently of the sequence being sliced\n",
    "The equivalent range only calculated once the length of the sequence being sliced is known\n",
    "\n",
    "Ex/\n",
    "[0:100] l sequence of length 10 -> range(0, 10)\n",
    "        l sequence of length 6 -> range(0, 6)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "d825390b-3e84-4dbc-aef1-bd6eb4599a5c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Transformations [i:j]\n",
    "\n",
    "The effective indices generated by a slice dependent on lenth of the sequence being slices\n",
    "Python does t his by rediucing the slice using the following rules\n",
    "\n",
    "    0    1    2    3    4    5\n",
    "l = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e', 'f']\n",
    "   -6   -5   -4   -3   -2   -1\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "seq[i:j]\n",
    "lenth = 6\n",
    "\n",
    "if i > len(seq) -> len(seq)\n",
    "if j > len(seq) -> len(seq)\n",
    "[0:100] -> range(0, 6)\n",
    "\n",
    "if i < 0 -> max(0, len(seq) + i)\n",
    "if j < 0 -> max(0, len(seq) + j)\n",
    "[-10:3] -> range(0, 3)\n",
    "[-5:3] -> range(1, 3)\n",
    "\n",
    "i omitted or None -> 0 \n",
    "[:100] -> range(0, 6)\n",
    "\n",
    "j omitted or None -> len(seq)\n",
    "[3:] -> range(3, 6)\n",
    "[:] -> range(0, 6)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "8decc204-9810-4cc7-a024-5bc958f8d64c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Transformations [i:j:k], k > 0\n",
    "\n",
    "With extended slicing things change depending on whether k is negative or positive\n",
    "\n",
    "[i:j:k] = {x = i + n*k | 0 <= n < (j-i)/k}\n",
    "k > 0 the indices are: i, i + k, i + 2k, ..., < j\n",
    "Stopping at j is reached or exceeded but never including j itself\n",
    "\n",
    "    0    1    2    3    4    5\n",
    "l = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e', 'f']\n",
    "   -6   -5   -4   -3   -2   -1\n",
    "\n",
    "if i, j > len(seq) -> len(seq)\n",
    "[0:100:2] -> range(0, 6, 2)\n",
    "\n",
    "if i, j < 0 -> max(0, len(seq) + i/j)\n",
    "[-10:100:2] -> range(0, 6, 2)\n",
    "[-5:100:2] -> range(1, 6, 2)\n",
    "\n",
    "i omitted or None -> 0\n",
    "[:6:2] -> range(0, 6, 2)\n",
    "\n",
    "j omitted or None -> len(seq)\n",
    "[1::2] -> range(1, 6, 2)\n",
    "[::2] -> range(0, 6, 2)\n",
    "\n",
    "So same rules as [i:j] - makes sense since that would be the same as [i:j:1]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "59bf8f30-5232-4c93-bcf2-415b7798bce1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Transformations [i:j:k], k < 0\n",
    "\n",
    "[i:j:k] = {x = i + n*k | 0 <= n < (j-i)/k}\n",
    "k < 0 the indices are: i, i + k, i + 2k, ..., > j\n",
    "\n",
    "    0    1    2    3    4    5\n",
    "l = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e', 'f']\n",
    "   -6   -5   -4   -3   -2   -1\n",
    "\n",
    "if i, j > len(seq) -> len(seq) - 1\n",
    "[5:2:-1] -> range(5, 2, -1)\n",
    "[10:2;-1] -> range(5, 2, -1)\n",
    "\n",
    "if i, j < 0 -> max(-1, len(seq) + i/j)\n",
    "[5:-2:-1] -> range(5, 4, -1)\n",
    "[-2:-5:-1] -> range(4, 1, -1)\n",
    "[-2:-10:-1] -> range(4, -1, -1)\n",
    "\n",
    "i omitted or None -> len(seq) - 1\n",
    "[:2:-1] -> range(5, 4, -1)\n",
    "\n",
    "j omitted or None -> -1\n",
    "[5::-1] -> range(5, -1, -1)\n",
    "[::-1] -> range(5, -1, -1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "44ea7fe7-4cc9-4a33-b174-ddfdd93b532f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "                         [i:j] or [i:j:k] k > 0        [i:j:k] k < 0\n",
    " \n",
    "i > len(seq)                     len(seq)               len(seq) - 1\n",
    "j > len(seq)                     len(seq)               len(seq) - 1\n",
    "\n",
    "i < 0                       max(0, len(seq)+i)      max(-1, len(seq)+i)\n",
    "j < 0                       max(0, len(seq)+j)      max(-1, len(seq)+j)\n",
    "\n",
    "i omitted/None                      0                    len(seq) - 1\n",
    "j omitted/None                  len(seq)                     -1"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "f96d8a91-9fd7-46a6-9a3e-5f844a2c8555",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Examples\n",
    "\n",
    "    0    1    2    3    4    5\n",
    "l = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e', 'f']\n",
    "   -6   -5   -4   -3   -2   -1\n",
    "\n",
    "length = 6\n",
    "\n",
    "[-10:10:1]\n",
    "-10 -> 0\n",
    "10 -> 6\n",
    "-> range(0, 6)\n",
    "\n",
    "[10:-10:-1]\n",
    "10 -> 5\n",
    "-10 -> max(-1, -4) -> -1\n",
    "-> range(5, -1, -1)\n",
    "\n",
    "We can easily define empty slices!\n",
    "\n",
    "[3:-1:-1]\n",
    "3 -> 3\n",
    "-1 -> max(-1, 5) -> 5\n",
    "-> range(3, 5, -1) -> []\n",
    "\n",
    "seq = sequence of length 6\n",
    "\n",
    "seq[::-1]\n",
    "i omitted -> len(seq) - 1 -> 5\n",
    "j omitted -> -1\n",
    "-> range(5, -1, -1) -> 5, 4, 3, 2, 1, 0\n",
    "\n",
    "seq = 'python'\n",
    "seq[::-1] = 'nohtyp'"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "7ff339bc-b6fb-4066-b7ed-70ca7b00d1f6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "If you get confused...\n",
    "\n",
    "The slice object has a method, indices, that returns the equivalent range start/stop/step for any slice given the length of the sequence being sliced:\n",
    "\n",
    "slice(start, stop, step).indices(length) -> (start, stop, step)\n",
    "\n",
    "The values in typle can be used to generate list of indices using range function\n",
    "\n",
    "slice(10, -5, -1) with sequence of length 6\n",
    "i = 10 > 6 -> 6 -1 -> 5\n",
    "j = -5 < 0 -> max(-1, 6 - 5) -> max(-1, 1) -> \n",
    "-> range(5, 1, -1)\n",
    "-> 5, 4, 3, 2\n",
    "\n",
    "slice(10, -5, -1).indices(6) -> (5, 1, -1)\n",
    "list(range(*slice(10, -5, -1).indices(6))) -> [5, 4, 3, 2]"
   ]
  },
